,"Abt 1215":"circa 1215","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1260":"1260","1208":"1208","South Benfleet, Essex, England":"South Benfleet, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1215–Bef 1296":"about 1215–before 1296","1215–1296":"1215–1296","1230–1296":"1230–1296","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1204–Male":"1204–Deceased","1208–Female":"1208–Deceased","Bef 1296":"before 1296","1305":"1305","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","Abt 1260":"about 1260","Abt 1215":"about 1215","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1260":"1260","1208":"1208","South Benfleet, Essex, England":"South Benfleet, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Laurance","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French form of Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from Laurentum’. <i>Laurentum</i> was a town in Latium, which may have got its name from Latin <i>laurus</i> ‘laurel’, although it is more probably of pre-Roman origin. The given name was moderately popular in the Middle Ages (when it was used for girls as well as boys), under the influence of a 3rd-century saint who was one of the seven deacons of Rome. He was martyred in  258 . The legend is that, having been required to hand over the Church's treasures to the civil authorities, he assembled the poor and sick and presented them. For this act of Christian defiance, he was roasted to death on a gridiron. In England the name is also associated with  St Laurence of Canterbury  (  d. 619 ). A more recent influence has been the actor  Sir Laurence Olivier  (  1907–89 ).  See also  Lawrence ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Laurance Plumbergh was born about 1215, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas de Plumbergh, was 13 and his mother, Maud de Bemflete, was 9. He had at least 1 daughter with Isabel de Plumbergh. He died before 1296, in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1215–Bef 1296":"umbes 1